properties.name: Pulgas Water Temple
properties.description: 1930s structure and viewing pond to celebrate the completion of the Hetch Hetchy water system supplying San Francisco.

properties.name: SF Bay Ferry
properties.description: Excellent views under the Bay Bridge, past the Port of Oakland, etc., depending on route. Subsidized as a disaster preparedness program in order to provide emergency transport in case bridges are damaged in a major earthquake. Easily the most pleasant way to cross the Bay.

properties.name: Altamont Pass wind farm
properties.description: Notable for being one of the first windfarms in the US.

properties.name: Monticello Dam, Lake Berryessa
properties.description: A relatively small dam but easy to get to and to see without any special access. Famous glory hole.

properties.name: View of ODock from the Steel Bridge’s sidewalk
properties.description:
A good from-above view of bulk carrier operations without any special permission needed. Mostly this is wheat going to Asia.

Steel Bridge is also notable for allowing pedestrians to stand very near the mechanism when it opens for passing ships.

properties.name: Bethany Reservoir
properties.description: Probably the easiest way to get close to the California Aqueduct at ground level (i.e., not just driving over it) from the inner Bay Area. $10 parking fee.

properties.name: Methane flare
properties.description: The park is built partly on a landfill; this prevents buildup (and lowers the CO2e of the methane by burning it).

properties.name: PDX parking lot roof
properties.description: Outstanding planespotting.

properties.name: Cross Channel electricity cable landing point
properties.description: There isn't much to see here - other than the door - but if you're here anyway maybe you want to say you've been here...

properties.name: Manchester Beach cable landing site
properties.description:
If you go down on the beach, you can find several old cables sticking out of the bluff.

See https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2015/11/where-the-cloud-rises-from-the-sea/415236/.

Not worth the trip unless you’re already on the 1, frankly.

properties.name: Middle Harbor
properties.description: One of several good shipspotting areas in the Port of Oakland.

properties.name: Mt Tabor reservoirs
properties.description: No interpretive installations, but an interesting walk. Mt Tabor is geologically interesting – it’s a volcano, part of the Boring Lava Field.

properties.name: Washington Park (Zoo) MAX station
properties.description: One of the deepest rail stations in the world, despite being on a rail system that’s almost entirely aboveground. Small but interesting selection of interpretive material (e.g., drilled cores) in the station.

properties.name: Karl G. Jansky Very Large Array Visitor Center
Willamette Stone State Heritage Site
properties.description: Origin point of surveys in the region.

properties.name: Atacama Large Millimeter Array - ALMA Radio Telescope
Dinorwig Power Station
properties.description: Formerly offered tours but no longer does.

properties.name: Mount Diablo Summit Museum and Trailhead
properties.description: Origin point for surveys in a large part of California. Outstanding views – sometimes rumored to be one of the largest viewsheds in the world, although this is easily debunked. Go on the clearest day possible to maximize vistas in all directions. A fun though scary drive on cliff-hugging roads designed in an era of smaller, slower cars. Has various temporary attractions such as tarantula season (early fall).

properties.name: PK Porthcurno
properties.description:
MUSEUM OF GLOBAL COMMUNICATIONS

Many transatlantic cables land here, and there's a museum in some old landing buildings.

properties.name: Tillamook Creamery
properties.description: Self-guided cheese factory tour.

properties.name: Four Corners Monument
properties.description: The only quadripoint of US states.

properties.name: K.R. Flower Market
properties.description: Notable for many reasons, e.g., the first building in Asia to have electrical lighting.

properties.name: The Castle
properties.description: An imposing victorian pumping station now converted into a climbing center - you can pop in and look around

properties.name: Kempegowda Metro Station Majestic
properties.description: Notable for its size and complexity.

properties.name: John Snow Water Pump
properties.description: Memorial water pump for John Snow who made maps of cholera infections and worked out they were spread by dirty water. Next door to a nice pub.

properties.name: Calshot Spit
properties.description: Activities centre includes some displays about the spit's use as a seaplane base. Also Calshot Castle next door, a beach, a good place to watch cruise ships and cargo ships, plus a radar tower with a National Coastwatch Institute watch station.

properties.name: Royal Victoria Country Park and Historic Hospital
properties.description:
Country Park on the site of old hospital used in WW1 by Florence Nightingale. Most of hospital burnt down in the 1960s. Chapel is left with a museum in it, plus tower access sometimes.

Miniature railway also there.

properties.name: Marmes Rockshelter
properties.description: Submerged by accident.

properties.name: Dounreay Nuclear Power Station Viewing Platform
Willamette Falls Scenic Viewpoint
properties.description: One of the largest waterfalls in the world by volume, but kind of charmingly modest in actual appearance: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Willamette_Falls

properties.name: 33 Thomas Street / Long Lines building
properties.description: Windowless skyscraper containing major communication exchange points, and the likely location of an NSA intercept hub codenamed TITANPOINTE. https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/33_Thomas_Street

properties.name: Marfa, Texas
properties.description: A small town that has become a magnet for arts, culture, and eccentricity. A popular road trip stop. Good place to see an art car.

properties.name: Hastings Cliff Railway - The West Hill Lift
Hastings Cliff Railway - East Hill Lift
Funikularea
properties.description: Take the funicular up for a great view over San Sebastian

properties.name: The Pittock Block
properties.description: Home of Portland’s internet exchange site. Many cables come ashore on the nearby coast, and many cloud-based companies have data centers in the Pacific Northwest, so it’s a larger interchange than you would expect for a mid-sized city. No tours that I know of.

properties.name: Portland Loo
properties.description: Example of a heavily used Portland Loo, a distinctive kind of public toilet: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Portland_Loo

properties.name: FAST Fiberglass Mold Graveyard
properties.description: Bizarre place you can explore where they keep all the old fibreglass moulds from years gone by just lying around outside. Visit!

properties.name: Gas Works Park
properties.description: An unremarkable city park except it has a huge rusting gasworks in it.

properties.name: Point Reyes Lighthouse
properties.description: Other interesting things on Point Reyes include sea lions.

properties.name: Redwood Valley Railway (Tilden Steam Train)
properties.description: Ride a miniature train on a loop through a pleasant forest for about 12 minutes. Designed for families, but pleasant for unaccompanied adults too. The sort of attraction that feels like a holdover from an earlier generation – when it goes, we’ll all be amazed it lasted as long as it did. Many kindly elderly volunteers in overalls. A bargain at $4/person as of this writing.

properties.name: Hythe Pier
properties.description: Long pier out into Southampton Water. Has a railway running along it, and boat trips from the end to Town Quay in Southampton. Good place to watch ships leaving Southampton Docks.

properties.name: The Town Mill
properties.description: Working flour mill

properties.name: Norman Lockyer Observatory
properties.description: Astronomical observatory, regularly open to the public with lots of talks and observing evenings. The original owner discovered Helium on the Sun through spectroscopy.

properties.name: San Andreas Fault
properties.description: This stretch of 1, between Pt Reyes Station and Woodville, runs almost exactly along the San Andreas Fault. At any given moment the left wheels of your car might be on the Pacific Plate and the right wheels on the North American Plane.

properties.name: Vitra Slide Tower
properties.description:
Tall free slide tower by Carsten Höller
https://www.vitra.com/en-be/about-vitra/campus/architecture/architecture-vitra-slide-tower

properties.name: Verner-Panton-Weg
properties.description: There's a really picturesque walk back to Basel, with modern art sculptures dotted on the landscape along the way.

properties.name: Newport Transporter Bridge Visitor Centre
properties.description: Currently closed until 2024. See https://www.newport.gov.uk/heritage/en/Transporter-Bridge/Transporter-Bridge.aspx for details.

properties.name: Hills of Mt St Helens ash dredged from the Toutle River after the 1980 eruption
properties.description: You can buy souvenir vials of Mt St Helens ash in the area for $15 or something, as my father would always point out when we drove past these.

properties.name: Evergreen Point Floating Bridge
properties.description: The longest and widest floating bridge in the world.

properties.name: Aldercrest-Banyon landslide site
properties.description: A very slow-moving landslide in 1998–99 that caused ~$100 million in damage. See https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aldercrest-Banyon_landslide

properties.name: Surviving Martin Mars Water Bombers
properties.description: The world’s largest firefighting flying boats.

properties.name: Roosevelt Island Tramway
properties.description:
Aerial tramway connecting Roosevelt Island to the Upper East Side of Manhattan. Visit the awesome 1970's architecture of Roosevelt Island

https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roosevelt_Island_Tramway

properties.name: Roosevelt Island Tramway - Island station
properties.description:
Aerial tramway connecting Roosevelt Island to the Upper East Side of Manhattan. Visit the awesome 1970's architecture of Roosevelt Island

https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roosevelt_Island_Tramway

properties.name: Island White
properties.description:
Oil wells and processing installations on islands right off the beach of Long Beach, disguised to look like a cross between a desert island (palm trees!) and generic mid-20th-century conference site (slightly angled concrete panels and structures), with a sprinkling of "evil lair"

https://la.curbed.com/2018/9/28/17858248/history-long-beach-oil-islands-thums

properties.name: Terminal Island
properties.description: Infrastructure on infrastructure on an island built just to be infrastructure.

properties.name: Romney Hythe & Dymchurch Railway
properties.description: Narrow gauge railway (runs towards Dungeness where you can see the power station, sound mirrors and more)

properties.name: Williamson Tunnels Heritage Centre
properties.description: Website seems to be partly broken, but tours can still be booked by phone.

properties.name: National Fruit Collection
properties.description:
Tours and events at the national collection of fruit trees.


Next level fruit knowledge. Head down around harvest time (they have cherry days, apple days etc).

Nice day trip from London on the high speed train, easy stroll from Faversham station to Brogdale Farm. Repair to the beer garden at the Sun Inn for a pint of Shepherd's Neame afterwards.

See https://brogdalecollections.org/

properties.name: Phone box at the centre of Great Britain
properties.description:
Phone box with a plaque in it marking the geographic centre of Great Britain.

See https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/5031162 and https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/5031165

properties.name: Orford Ness
properties.description: Military test site, inc bomb test chambers and the fantastically-named Cobra Mist experimental radar station. Various remains still visible.

properties.name: Remains of Mulberry Harbours in Rigg Bay
properties.description: Remains of some of the parts of the Mulberry floating harbours used in the D-Day invasion. More details at https://mulberryharbour.info/

properties.name: Pentrich Revolution Trail
properties.description:
Trail around sites involved in the Pentrich Revolution - an armed uprising that took place in 1817.

Walking guide: https://info.ambervalley.gov.uk/docarc/docviewer.aspx?docGuid=3514f6233182445c93afa6edca209e46

properties.name: Tim Hunkin's Under Pier Show - Southwold Pier
properties.description:
Welcome to the utterly eccentric world of Tim Hunkin’s machines.

Where else in the world can you experience the life of a fly in VR, train for your future on a Zimmer frame simulator, or take out your frustrations with the financial industry on the ‘Whack A Banker’ machine (it’s really very cathartic) all in one room?

The Under the Pier Show is one of the most unique and eccentric collections of interactive machines in the world; weirdly wonderful inventions which have sprung from the genius brain of Tim Hunkin. There are nearly twenty for you to try – and you’ll want to try them all!

properties.name: Sheldon Country Park - Birmingham Airport viewing area
properties.description: Seats at the end of the runway of Birmingham Airport. Park at Marston Green Railway Station, take a picnic and watch the planes.

properties.name: The Cascades
properties.description: Where the water from the Owens River Aqueduct gets aerated and enters Los Angeles in a giant waterfall.

properties.name: Dunwich
properties.description:
Formerly the 'Capital of East Anglia' (c. 1500) this Suffolk town was one of the most important UK sea ports. It was in the top 10 'largest places in England' and had a population of 3000.

However, it has rapidly fallen into the sea (and continues to do so) with only a handful of houses and 120 residents remaining. Notable places to visit currently include the museum and 17th century traditional pub.

Is a fascinating place to visit, so I would recommend going before it's all gone!

properties.name: Scott Russell Aqueduct
properties.description: Location of the first sighting of a 'soliton wave' - see https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Soliton

properties.name: Electric Brae
properties.description:
A 'gravity hill', where it looks like objects roll up hill. It's actually an optical illusion. Engraved stone marks the site and explains how it works.

See https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electric_Brae

properties.name: Reigate Caves
properties.description: Interesting former sand mines which have had many uses (known and unknown) over the years.

properties.name: Middlesbrough Transporter Bridge
properties.description:
Transporter bridge over the River Tees. Visitors centre open, but bridge currently undergoing repairs.

See https://www.middlesbrough.gov.uk/parking-roads-and-footpaths/tees-transporter-bridge

properties.name: Smedley Street WW2 Resistance HQ
properties.description: Between 1939 to 1945, Burton House, a building on Smedley Street Matlock, played an undercover role during the war as the headquarters for Matlock’s Secret Army. There is a blue plaque commemorating this.

properties.name: Ossuary in the Crypt of St Leonard's church
properties.description: One of only two ossuaries in the UK. See https://www.slhk.org/theossuary.htm

properties.name: Anti-Aircraft Battery Blantyreferme
properties.description:
Remains of a gun battery from WW2.

See https://www.secretscotland.org.uk/index.php/Secrets/AABatteryBlantyreferme

properties.name: The Big Hole
properties.description: A big hole from diamond mining. The museum is interesting as well.

properties.name: Great Zimbabwe
properties.description: Ruins of a fort

properties.name: WGS84 Prime Meridian Picnic Spot
properties.description:
The showy lines in the Greenwich Observatory do not represent the current Prime Meridian. If you want your GPS to be as close to zero as possible, head a little bit east from the observatory. 

This is a nice spot to have a picnic right on the Prime Meridian. It is roughly between the two big trees that are at this spot. Under the trees, your GPS will wander a bit due to multipath signals, so you may need to move due south or due north from here for an accurate fix.

properties.name: KivuWatt
properties.description:
Power station based on extracting (potentially extremely dangerous) methane from deep in the lake: https://www.nature.com/immersive/d41586-021-02523-5/index.html

Or: https://theconversation.com/rwanda-extracts-methane-from-lake-kivu-for-electricity-how-it-works-133952

properties.name: Charleston Tea Garden
properties.description: One of very few tea operations in North America.

properties.name: Bridge of the Americas
properties.description: This bridge’s clearance defines the maximum height of Panamax ships.

properties.name: Tilikum Crossing Bridge
properties.description: In Wikipedia’s words: “It is the first major bridge in the U.S. that was designed to allow access to transit vehicles, cyclists and pedestrians but not cars.”

properties.name: Aerial tram (lower terminal)
properties.description: A short but fun aerial tram, with good views. Unfortunately, there’s not that much for a tourist to do on either end. Reasonably well connected to other transit, though.

properties.name: Laxey Wheel
properties.description: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laxey_Wheel

properties.name: Wainhouse Tower
properties.description:
Magnificent 19thC folly, tallest structure in Calderdale, and claimed to be the tallest folly in the world.
http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wainhouse_Tower

properties.name: The Rollright Stones
properties.description: A small stone circle (The Kingsmen), the King Stone and a neolithic burial chamber. http://www.rollrightstones.co.uk

properties.name: Derby Arboretum (Arboretum Park)
properties.description: The first public park in England. The landscaping was influential on the design of Central Park in New York some years later.

properties.name: Purton Ship Graveyard
properties.description: A 'graveyard' of barges beached to shore up the banks of the Gloucester and Sharpness Canal alongside the River Severn.

properties.name: Foredown Tower
properties.description: A camera obscura in a former water tower. Foredown Rd Portslade, Brighton East Sussex BN41 2EW United Kingdom 01273 292 092

properties.name: Creswell Crags
properties.description: Cave art from nearly 13,000 years ago, the only cave art from that period in the UK.

properties.name: Imber
properties.description: Village pinched from the villagers by the MoD in 1943 for training and never given back. Access is occasional (a few days a year).

properties.name: Guys Cliffe House
properties.description: Ruined ancient house that burnt down. Dramatic views from The Saxon Mill pub (which really is a working Mill, with water wheel and mill pond)

properties.name: Murray Star Maze
properties.description: Glorious pentagonal maze with tartan hedge pattern. Accompanying palace of Scone features albino peacocks and a collection of historic papier-maché vases.

properties.name: Hut of the shaddows
properties.description:
and-built stone and turf camera obscura on the lochside. Access by foot over suspension bridge.
http://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/1438241

properties.name: The Big Dipper: Europe's 2nd largest sand dune
Anchor Church
properties.description: A series of sandstone caves that have been carved into the rock. http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anchor_Church

properties.name: Bingley Five Rise Locks
properties.description:
Five Rise Locks - Canal walk/bike ride with a cafe at the top, bonus :) http://www.bingley.org.uk/around/locks.htm

(you might want to push your bike up, and coming down could be hairy for those at the bottom)

properties.name: Neptune's Staircase
properties.description: Thomas Telford's amazing series of 8 locks raises boats 70 feet above sea level across 500 yards. Excellent views of Ben Nevis thrown in as an added bonus.

properties.name: Royal Mills
properties.description:
Walk around these mills in Ancoats and you understand what the Prussian architect Friedrich Karl Schinkel felt in 1825, when he marvelled: "the enormous factory buildings are seven to eight storeys high...where three years ago there were only meadows"
http://www.manchester2002-uk.com/history/victorian/Victorian3.html

properties.name: Bradwell Power Plant Shell Beach
properties.description: Now decommissioned, this nuclear power station was built in the 1950s and quietly dominates the surrounding rural landscape. Walk eastwards from here, along a lovely shell covered beach, past WW2 pill boxes and sunken barges (to prevent coastal erosion) until you reach the atmospheric 7th century St Peter's chapel. Nerds will relish this surreal journey backwards in time, from modern nuclear science to ancient spritualism.

properties.name: House in the Clouds
properties.description: Built as a folley come water tower, the House in the Clouds is a landmark in Thorpeness. Also available as holiday accommodation.

properties.name: Kilnsea Sound Mirror
properties.description:
World War 2 sound mirror used to detect approaching aircraft.

See http://www.andrewgrantham.co.uk/soundmirrors/locations/kilnsea/

properties.name: Emley Moor Tower
properties.description: The tallest free standing building in the UK - the Emley Moor transmitting station http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Emley_Moor_transmitting_station

properties.name: Horsell Common sand pits
properties.description: Not much to actually *see*, in the traditional sense, but this is where the Martians first land in HG Wells' War of the Worlds. Worth a pilgrimage if you're that way inclined.

properties.name: Tickford Bridge
properties.description:
Built in 1810 is the only Iron bridge in Britain that still carries main road traffic and is the oldest iron bridge in the world that is still in constant use.

http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tickford_Bridge

properties.name: Wolverton Works Canal Bridge
properties.description: Early cast iron girder bridge: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wolverton_Works_canal_bridge

properties.name: Haslingden Halo
properties.description:
A 18m-diameter steel lattice structure, lit after dark by blue LEDs powered by a nearby wind-turbine.

http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Panopticons#Haslingden_Halo

properties.name: Singing Ringing Tree
properties.description: The Singing Ringing Tree is a wind powered sound sculpture resembling a tree set in the landscape of the Pennine hill range overlooking Burnley, in Lancashire, England.

properties.name: Lapstone Zig Zag
properties.description: Remains of old zig-zag railway up into Blue Mountains. Includes abandoned Lucasville Station. Also near the historic Knapsack bridge, visit the strange Victorian mineshaft - dug for unkown reasons...

properties.name: Cockatoo Island
properties.description: An abandoned ex-prison and dockyard. Now used as an unusal camp-site and for art-installation projects. Worth visitng just for the tunnels through solid rock.

properties.name: Glen Roy National Nature Reserve - Glacial Remains
properties.description: Remnants of shorelines of a glacial lake, visible half way up the mountain. See https://www.nature.scot/enjoying-outdoors/visit-our-nature-reserves/glen-roy-national-nature-reserve

properties.name: Braefoot Point
properties.description: World War I Coastal Battery, with a nice view of the the oil terminal.

properties.name: Tyneham Village
properties.description: Village taken over for military training in WW2. Open on various days.

properties.name: Alan Turing Memorial
properties.description: Statue commemorating Alan Turing in the pleasant Sackville Street Gardens.

properties.name: Murrays Beach
properties.description: Intended as the site of Australia's nuclear power plant. Now part of Booderee National Park - part run by indigenous original owners of the land. Whole area is technically an independent territory, not part of NSW. Near by naval base intended as a port for the city of Canberra.

properties.name: Anita Street Municipal housing development
properties.description: Late Victorian municipal housing development; was originally going to be named Sanitary Street, but the residents didn't like it and 'S' and 'ry' were dropped. When you are here, do also check out Victoria Square, the block at the eastern end of the street: the first example of municipal housing in Manchester.

properties.name: St Aldhelm's Chapel
properties.description:
Old Norman chapel, memorial to the development of radar, Coastguard station, who are happy to explain their work to passing visitors.

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/St._Aldhelm%27s_Chapel,_St._Aldhelm%27s_Head

properties.name: Grave of J.P. Joule
properties.description: Joule died at home in Sale and is buried in Brooklands cemetery there. The gravestone is inscribed with the number "772.55", his climacteric 1878 measurement of the mechanical equivalent of heat, and with a quotation from the Gospel of John, "I must work the works of him that sent me, while it is day: the night cometh, when no man can work" (9:4).

properties.name: Congress Avenue Bridge
properties.description: Known for its bats: https://www.austincityguide.com/listings/congress-bridge-bats

properties.name: MacArthur Maze
properties.description: One of the first and, it’s widely agreed, worst freeway interchanges in the US. Far more confusing than it needs to be for the relatively simple intersection it handles.

properties.name: The Transbay Tube
properties.description: The underwater route of the BART light rail system. Notable for lying on top of (or partially sunk into) the shallow Bay, instead of being a tunnel in the usual sense.

properties.name: Lighthouse Visitor Centre
properties.description: Includes very loud foghorn which is sometimes demonstrated.

properties.name: Birdsville combined geothermal and drinking water system
Grand Central Terminal
properties.description: Beautiful art deco terminal station

properties.name: The High Line
properties.description: Pedestrian path converted from an old rail line, an excellent walk in NYC

properties.name: Patterson–Gimlin Film Site
properties.description: The most famous video “evidence” of Sasquatch.

properties.name: Tena Bar, where money from the D.B. Cooper skyjacking was found
properties.description: Pin location not exact.

properties.name: Takaosan interchange
properties.description: A particularly interesting-looking interchange that occasionally goes viral, either for looking interesting (dusk lighting, autumn colors, etc.) or for looking scary (e.g. https://www.snopes.com/fact-check/takaosan-interchange-tokyo/).

properties.name: Janni’s Chimney
properties.description: A small, rich silver mine abandoned in mildly mysterious circumstances: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Northport,_Washington#Janni's_chimney

properties.name: The Bathysphere
properties.description:
Just to the left of the entrance to the New York Aquarium is the Bathysphere, the first spherical deep-sea submersible. It set many diving records, and was the first underwater vehicle used by a marine biologist to observe deep-sea animals in their native environment. 

It was the main display of the New York Zoological Society at the 1939 World's Fair, and has been on display in Coney Island sporadically since 1957. 

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bathysphere

properties.name: The Bay Lights
properties.description: Art made using the lights on the cables of the western span of the Bay Bridge. Not operational as of this writing, but will return. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Bay_Lights

properties.name: Lower Baker Dam
properties.description: A modestly sized but undeniably striking dam close to a highway: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lower_Baker_Dam

properties.name: Black Panther Party stoplight
properties.description: See https://www.hmdb.org/m.asp?m=72395 or https://localwiki.org/oakland/55th_and_Market_Traffic_Light – a minor event, but important in the history of the BPP; it showed its ability to do infrastructural things, and contributed momentum that led toward Free Breakfast for Children and other major projects.

properties.name: West Edmonton Mall
properties.description: One of the largest malls in the world by various measures. In essence, they took a shopping district and put a giant building around it.

properties.name: Berry Head Lighthouse
properties.description:
The UK's shortest, but also highest lighthouse. The light is barely above ground level, but the lighthouse is one of the highest above sea level.

See https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Berry_Head_Lighthouse

properties.name: Cuckfield Royal Observer Corps Bunker
properties.description: https://www.facebook.com/Cuckfieldnuclearbunker/ for details of regular open days

properties.name: Beckton Sewage Treatment Works
properties.description: Often open during Open House

properties.name: Southwark Integrated Waste Management Facility
properties.description: Southwark residents can book a tour. Also often open during Open House.

properties.name: South East London Combined Heat & Power Ltd
properties.description: Often open during Open House

properties.name: Westray Community Wind Turbine
properties.description: Run by Westray Renewable Energy Ltd with proceeds going to the local community. https://westraydevelopmenttrust.co.uk/westray-renewable-energy-ltd/

properties.name: Seafield waste water treatment works
properties.description: Has opened on Doors Open Day in the past https://www.scottishwater.co.uk/About-Us/News-and-Views/2022/10/041022-Seafield-Doors-Open-Day

properties.name: Skye Ferry
properties.description:
The last manually operated steel turntable ferry in the world.

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MV_Glenachulish

properties.name: Donside Hydro
properties.description:
Small community-owned hydro plant, with an archimedes screw turbine. You can also access the artificial island on the far side of the lade.
https://acenergy.org.uk/

properties.name: Isle of May lighthouse
properties.description: A Robert Stephenson lighthouse. Open to visitors. https://www.nlb.org.uk/lighthouses/isle-of-may/

properties.name: Portsmouth to Ryde hovercraft terminal
properties.description: https://www.hovertravel.co.uk/

properties.name: Corrour Station House
properties.description: A station in Rannoch Moor, only accessible by rail or 20 mile walk. There is accommodation in the old signal box. https://www.corrour.co.uk/station-house/

properties.name: Dallas Pedestrian Network
properties.description: A slightly abandoned network of underground and overground tunnels linking many buildings in Downtown Dallas. Cool to explore and have a creepy walk around...

properties.name: McMenamins Roseburg Station Pub & Brewery
properties.description: Gastro/brewpub in a former train station, with a lot of historical photos and minor artifacts. There’s a self-guided tour (http://cms.mcmenamins.com/files/History/Roseburg/history.roseburg.phototour.pdf – basically a photo key) on their site. Recommended if you’re stopping in Roseburg but not worth going out of your way.

properties.name: Dakin Building
properties.description: One of the more interesting nondescript office buildings. Its Wikipedia article’s headings include “Role during Glasnost” and “The Star Wars saga”: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dakin_Building

properties.name: Astoria-Megler Bridge
properties.description: The longest continuous truss bridge in North America. Interesting for the unusual combination of being long (6.5 km or 4 mi) and, in one section (on the southern/Astoria end), having high clearance.

properties.name: Amoreiras Mother of Water Reservoir
properties.description: Recommend doing the tour of the Loreto Gallery, suggest booking in advance.

properties.name: Prague Metronome
Null Island

properties.name: Sousse Archaeological Museum
properties.description:
A museum and ancient structure in one!

It is mostly devoted to Roman/Byzantine mosaics, and the Byzantine baptismal font is worth a visit alone.

Sadly, you can't see much of the kasbah itself, rather than admiring it from the outside (it's beautifully lit at night, with a functioning lighthouse). If you want to explore a similar structure, head to the Sousse Ribat on the other side of the medina. (The mosque isn't worth a visit, sadly).

Allow an hour or two for a visit. The parking is free, and at the time of writing (2023) was also the best place for overnight parking for the medina.

Added by grajohnt

properties.name: Great Mosque of Kairouan
properties.description:
Fascinating mosque on its surface, just for the history, but look deeper and it's even more interesting. It is considered a masterpiece of Islamic architecture, but lacks the adornments common in later buildings. The 'uncountable' columns that hold up the vaulted ceilings are clearly reused Roman/Byzantine columns with a wild assortment of capitals and materials. Each one is a bit different in height, so they made up the difference with bricks before building the brick vaulted ceilings. There is carved Latin text (some upside-down) on the courtyard side of the minaret that clearly demonstrates the reuse of older material.

The whole courtyard is a rainwater collection system, and there are circular wells on the north end of the courtyard where you can peek down into the massive cisterns built underneath.

The little staircase in the middle of the courtyard leads to a sundial, which is also worth a look.

Worth at least half an hour to look around - more if you're really into Roman columns.

Added by grajohnt

properties.description: For years was the tallest lift-locks in the world.  Lovely parklands around too, nice place to stop if you're in the area

properties.name: Maunsell Forts

WWII giant iron forts in the English channel. Needs a private boat to get to them.

properties.name: Ruins of RAF Stoney Cross

Lots of bits of taxiways and runways available (look on satellite view), old lighting structures etc. The main runway is now the suspiciously straight road. Lots of pleasant New Forest scenery, plus ice cream vans, and local ponds/lakes.

properties.name: Ramsgate Hoverport Remains

properties.name: Pontcysyllte Aqueduct
properties.description: Nice canal basin/boat yard at one end, with a little shop for ice creams etc. One of the cottages alongside the canal is a holiday cottage which is a nice place to stay.

properties.name: Walthamstow Pumphouse Museum
properties.description: This used to be a sewage pumping station, and is now being run as a museum by a group of (mostly elderly) hobbyist, who are more than happy to explain all the details. Last I checked they were also working on a model rail replicate of the old Walthamstow Street Station.

properties.name: Middlesex Filter Beds Nature Reserve
properties.description: A historic sewage treatment site that has been turned into a nature reserve and park. The center-piece is a round filterbed where each side is in a different state of 're-wilding'. 1-2 hours max, can get quite busy on nice days. You can combine it with a stroll along the canal towards the Olypmic park.

properties.name: Hackney Power Station

properties.name: West Kennet Long Barrow
properties.description:
One of the largest, most impressive and most accessible Neolithic chambered tombs in Britain. Built in around 3650 BC, it was used for a short time as a burial chamber, nearly 50 people being buried here before the chambers were blocked. Part of the Avebury World Heritage Site. Open constantly.

See https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/visit/places/west-kennet-long-barrow/

properties.name: Silbury Hill
properties.description:
The largest artificial mound in Europe, mysterious Silbury Hill compares in height and volume to the roughly contemporary Egyptian pyramids. Probably completed in around 2400 BC, it apparently contains no burial. Though clearly important in itself, its purpose and significance remain unknown.

https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/visit/places/silbury-hill/

properties.name: Avebury Stone Circles
properties.description:
Avebury henge and stone circles are one of the greatest marvels of prehistoric Britain. Built and much altered during the Neolithic period, roughly between 2850 BC and 2200 BC, the henge survives as a huge circular bank and ditch, encircling an area that includes part of Avebury village. Within the henge is the largest stone circle in Britain - originally of about 100 stones - which in turn encloses two smaller stone circles.

See https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/visit/places/avebury/

properties.description:
Wildly ambitious but never fully-built, designed as an 'arcology' - a dense space for living/working (hello "SimCity" fans).  The construction is from concrete panels that are cast in dirt and then tilted/lifted into position, but in much wilder shapes than modern tilt-wall buildings.

Full-on sci-fi vibes when you're there - open to the public year round, and has artists in residence.

Worth a stop!

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arcosanti

properties.name: Carthage (in general)
properties.description:
The ruins of Carthage are generally a disappointment, even if you're a Roman history buff. For the most part, they're in poor condition and poorly curated/explained. The various ruins are also pretty spread out. Still walkable, but you end up spending a lot of time getting from one slightly disappointing ruin to another.

The Carthage Museum is currently closed, and isn't scheduled to reopen until 2025 (?).

You probably still *have* to go see Carthage if you're in Tunis, so save yourself some time and hit the Baths of Antoninus. There's at least a bit of explaination there, and it's fun to scramble around a bit in the ruins.

Added by grajohnt

properties.name: Cisterns of La Malga
properties.description:
Far and away the most 'infrastructure-y' part of the ruins of Carthage, these are interesting for their size and scope, if not their beauty.

The cisterns are in pretty good shape, with one that has clearly undergone some modern restoration work. However, the aqueduct itself is very much in ruins, and it takes some imagination to see what it might have looked like.

There is no interpretation/explanation here, so read up in advance!

Worth a quick stop, but that's about it.

properties.name: Monastir Ribat
properties.description:
A really interesting structure in a fairly spectacular location. Lots of opportunity to explore the structure, including climbing to the top of the watch tower for a beautiful view of the beach, ocean, cemetary, and city. With several narrow, unrailed and uneven staircases, and the low ramparts on top of the tower, this probably isn't the place for those that are afraid of heights.

The museum doesn't hold much noteworthy, except for a few interesting coins.

Allow at least an hour or so to explore the whole ruin.

Added by grajohnt

properties.name: Amphitheater of El Jem
properties.description:
El Jem's Amphitheater and museum more than make up for the disappointment of Carthage, and it is well worth a special trip to see them.

The amphitheater is huge (3rd largest in the world), and at least has a little interpretation. You can climb all the way up to the highest levels and look down on the floor (and the town), and also explore the underground levels.

Honestly, it's better than the Roman Colosseum in many ways. Beautiful photography opportunities abound.

A 15 minute walk takes you to the museum, which is chock full of huge (room-sized) intact Roman mosaics. One of the best collections I've ever seen.

Worth at least an hour, two plus if you include the museum. A half day in El Jem is not out of order.

Added by grajohnt

properties.name: Historic Village Chebika
properties.description:
This is IMHO the best of the 'mountain oases' around Tozeur, and if you're short on time or deep interest, you can skip the others. Well worth the walk up the path to the spring/waterfall, and there's also stairs that go up to the hilltop above the village for a nice view.

Well worth a stop, allow at least an hour.

Added by grajohnt

properties.name: Mides Canyon / Oasis
properties.description:
A modestly pretty little canyon next to a bog-standard date palm oasis.

You can walk around the very end of the canyon from here, and if you walk up the hill a bit, you can get a view of an Algeria border post across the oasis to the north.

Not really worth a stop unless you're really keen on getting right up on the Algerian border. You can *probably* just walk across it here, but that's not necessarily a good idea.

Added by grajohnt

properties.name: Basins of Aghlabides
properties.description:
An essential part of the water infrastructure of Kairouan, remarkable for their preservation and antiquity (date back to 862 AD).

Unfortunately, they're hardly worth a visit. Stop by the Tourist Information Center (this pin) to buy a ticket that gets you into both here and the Great Mosque, pop up to the roof to get a photo, and leave. Spend your time at the Great Mosque instead.

It's also possible to walk around the site, but sadly the basins aren't that interesting to see and there's no interpretation.

properties.name: Curved elevator at the Old Town Hall
properties.description: The elevator to the viewing gallery is curved, but not evenly; it's been rebuilt and reshaped a couple of times.

properties.name: Ik Kil Cenote
properties.description: The central and northern Yucatán is made of such porous rock that, despite fairly plentiful rainfall, it has essentially no rivers or natural lakes – other than the cenotes. Among other things, this made cenotes hugely culturally important to the Classical Maya civilization.

properties.name: St. Johns Bridge
properties.description: Beautiful, locally beloved bridge. Longest suspension bridge west of the Mississippi at the time of construction. Other than the bridge itself (which can be crossed on foot), Cathedral Park, under it, is very pleasant of a summer evening.

properties.name: Vanport Marker
properties.description:
Housing for migrant workers, particularly Black people in the Great Migration, was built in this floodplain during WWII. When it inevitably flooded, the effort to recover was an epochal community-making event and a turning point in Oregon’s racial politics. Led more or less directly to Northeast being Portland’s Blackest quadrant, and to the establishment of Portland State University, just for two.

Little remains to be seen onsite, though people sometimes leave flowers and such.

properties.name: Flight 173 Memorial
properties.description:
A crash caused in large part by poor communication and lack of shared situational awareness among the flight crew. (They ran out of fuel while focusing on a landing gear malfunction.) The NTSB report contained recommendations that contributed heavily to the development of modern crew resource management (CRM) communications procedures.

Little is visible at the site, but given that it’s just a few blocks from a MAX stop, it’s a relatively easy pilgrimage for people interested in these things.

properties.name: Grand Central Stones
properties.description: In November 1905, the New York Central Railroad placed a series of stone samples in the open air on property the railroad controlled within Van Cortlandt Park. The purpose was to assess the effects of a New York winter on the samples of granite, limestone, and marble that the railroad and its architects, Reed & Stem and Warren & Wetmore, were considering for the exterior curtain wall of the head house of the new Grand Central Terminal, then under construction in midtown Manhattan.

A Pinnacles trip requires planning: Avoid busy times (like long weekends), beware of very high temperatures in summer, and bring supplies. With those caveats, the hiking is exceptionally enjoyable and spectacular. Bring binoculars to see condors and a number of other interesting birds.

properties.name: Wi:kchsawa / Superstition Mountains
properties.description:
Beautiful mountains, but notoriously dangerous. The heat is often extreme, the trails are exposed and exhausting (people forget they’re at elevation when they’re hot!), and the brush is deceptively thick, making it easy to get lost and take a step off a cliff. A truly alarming number of hikers have died here, and their remains often go unfound in the dense scrub and many tiny canyons.

Also the site of the folkloric lost Dutchman’s gold (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lost_Dutchman%27s_Gold_Mine), one of the more interesting and culturally important buried treasure stories of the West. In some versions, it’s a small but very rich gold seam; in others, it’s a cache of conquistador-looted gold hidden in a rock cleft by Apaches; presumably some people think it’s aliens. Over the last century or more, large numbers of treasure hunters have, unsurprisingly, died while offtrail in this exceptionally dangerous landscape. This has only fed the legends of curses and increased the perceived value of the gold. There are entire (fairly entertaining) books just about the histories of the various expeditions.

Arizona State Parks advises you to plan your hike carefully, particularly as regards your water supply, and to stay strictly on marked trails. This is good advice.

The full trail has a couple of these, and is a nice break to stretch your legs, if it's not too baking hot.

Also has unadvertised vault toilets just a few minutes up the trail, so makes a reasonable rest stop for that as well.

The Loma Prieta earthquake (1989) partially collapsed a two-level expressway that ran here. The local community, mostly impoverished Black people whose neighborhood the freeway had split, acted heroically, improvising ladders and other tools, pulling trapped drivers out of the wreckage, and administering first aid while EMTs were overloaded. This is one of very few memorials to peacetime community heroism in the world.

The route of the expressway is now Mandela Parkway, a more modest street with a long linear park in the median.

properties.name: Strait of Juan de Fuca boundary dispute
properties.description: Despite warm relations, the US and Canada manage to dispute areas at both ends of both their borders. (See https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_areas_disputed_by_Canada_and_the_United_States.) This is the smallest and probably least important: the countries disagree on how to draw the median line in two areas of the Exclusive Economic Zones outside the mouth of the Strait. In short, Canada includes its inland waters as contributing to the median line, while the US uses the low tide line. (See https://www.durham.ac.uk/media/durham-university/research-/research-centres/ibru-centre-for-borders-research/maps-and-databases/publications-database/boundary-amp-security-bulletins/bsb5-3_gray.pdf for a little more detail.) The total area in dispute is slightly over 50 km² and (so far as I know) has never led to any actual incidents.

properties.name: Star Wars: Mos Espa
properties.description:
You will never find a more wretch hive of touts and degraded Hollywood sets.

Look, I get it, you're in Tunisia, and you want to see Star Wars stuff. If you're in Touzeur, it's pretty easy to visit this spot, and hopefully it will get it out of your system.

Absolutely filled with touts offering camel tours and 4-wheeler excursions across the dunes, plus a smattering of shops with the same stuff you can find anywhere else.

You can walk around in the ruins of the Berber village and see some of the set additions made for Star Wars. These were clearly just barely good enough to work for a set, and are starting to get somewhat decrepit.

The drive out there is across the desert on a road that must be regularly 'plowed' to remove blowing sand. You will spend more time getting there than you do visiting, so enjoy this part!

properties.name: KTH R1
properties.description:
KTH Reactor Hall
The research reactor R1 is an experimental stage today, a creative venue for meetings between different disciplines.

The Reactor Hall originally housed Sweden’s first nuclear reactor, research reactor R1. It was operational between 1954 and 1970, and even though the reactor itself has long since been removed, the Reactor Hall still has an aura of research and experimentation.

Today, KTH uses the Reactor Hall as a combination of museum, culture centre, seminar room, studio, lab and more. Not least for activities with artistic university colleges in Stockholm. https://www.kth.se/en/thetale/standard-avdelning/kth-reaktorhallen-1.1135540
